Habitat. In Suriname
N. bilinearis
is locally common at rivers such as Corantijn-, Maratakka-, Marowijne-, Saramacca- and Tibitiriver and less frequent at creeks such as Siparikreek (
Table 1
), Wanekreek and Coropinakreek. Most Suriname records are from the savanna area. Fewer records are known from the interior, and only one record is known from the coastal area (Cupid at Maratakka). Most records are 25 to 100 km from the sea, but one record is known at a river 215 km into the interior (
Fig. 14
). In Brazil an abundant population was found in the Tucurui reservoir (
Machado 2004
), indicating that the species occurs in partly lentic as well as the more typical lotic water systems.
